  <h2>Food Pairing Guide</h2>

<p>Merlot's supple tannins and fruit-forward character create natural flavor bridges with a remarkable range of cuisines. The wine's medium body and moderate acidity make it one of the most food-friendly reds in any cellar.</p>

<h3>The Flavor Bridge</h3>
<p>Merlot's <strong>plush berry fruit and subtle earthiness</strong> complement both rich proteins and vegetable-forward dishes. The wine's soft tannin structure won't overpower delicate preparations, while its concentrated fruit can stand up to bold flavors. Look for ingredients that echo Merlot's core profile: dark fruits, herbs, mushrooms, and gentle spices.</p>

<h3>Classic Pairings</h3>
<ul class="space-y-2">
  <li><strong>Roasted duck with cherry sauce</strong> - The wine's natural cherry notes harmonize perfectly with the fruit reduction, while Merlot's acidity cuts through the rich, fatty duck</li>
  <li><strong>Grilled lamb with rosemary</strong> - Herbaceous Right Bank Merlots echo the rosemary's earthy aromatics, while the wine's structure complements lamb's tender texture</li>
  <li><strong>Mushroom risotto with truffle oil</strong> - Merlot's earthy undertones create a seamless bridge with umami-rich mushrooms and truffle's mineral complexity</li>
  <li><strong>Beef short ribs braised in red wine</strong> - The wine's concentrated fruit balances the rich, gelatinous texture while its tannins provide pleasant contrast</li>
</ul>

<h3>Regional Traditions</h3>
<p>In Bordeaux's Right Bank, Merlot traditionally pairs with <strong>confit de canard</strong> and aged Roquefort, where the wine's elegance doesn't compete with these intense flavors. Napa Valley producers often showcase their Merlots alongside <strong>grilled portobello mushrooms</strong> and herb-crusted rack of lamb.</p>

<h3>Everyday Versatility</h3>
<p>For casual dining, try Merlot with <strong>margherita pizza</strong> - the wine's acidity complements tomato sauce while its fruit echoes the basil's sweetness. <strong>Grilled salmon with herbs</strong> works beautifully, as does <strong>turkey meatballs in marinara</strong>, where Merlot's gentle tannins won't overwhelm the lighter protein.</p>

<h3>Special Occasions</h3>
<p>Reserve your finest Bordeaux Merlot for <strong>filet mignon with morel mushrooms</strong> or <strong>aged hard cheeses like Comté</strong>, where the wine's complexity can truly shine alongside equally sophisticated flavors.</p>

